photo.title: San Francisco Ferry Building

description._content:
Opening in 1898, the San Francisco Ferry building served as a major transit terminal for the Port of San Francisco, connecting it with areas around the Bay.  Until the completion of the Bay Bridge in the 1930s, the ferry building was the second busiest in the world behind London's Charing Cross Station.
While still serving as a ferry terminal, the building now also houses a variety of markets and food vendors, including the a well known Farmer's Market on Saturdays, Tuesdays, and Thursdays.

description._content: The San Francisco Ferry Building is a terminal for ferries that travel across the San Francisco Bay, a marketplace, and also has offices, located on The Embarcadero in San Francisco, California. description._content: Facebook | Website I headed over to Yerba Buena Island on Saturday to try and get some shots of the new eastern span of the Bay Bridge. It was a quiet day in the city, the first day of a three day Labor Day weekend. I met up with my friend Terence at the Temporary Transbay Terminal to take the 108 Muni across the bay. We did this exact same trip back in 2009 for another Bay Bridge closure, back when the S-Curve was just being moved into place. A lot has changed since 2009, most of all my camera and my experiences in photography, from my humble D40 days when I had yet to even really venture outside of California. Unfortunately, YBI has changed as well, and not really for the better (at least for photographers). The top of the island is a veritable fortress anymore, with signs everywhere from both the US coast guard and SFPD warning against trespassing. The area was always sort of off-limits, but they seem to be clamping down on unwanted guests. There's now some sort of shuttle for residents and new private security as well. I only know this 1) because we were offered a ride from the bus stop at the bottom of Macalla up the hill (lifesaver!) and 2) cause we were told to leave by said security at the end of the night. That run in was actually fortunate in that we got away with wandering all over the island for several hours beforehand. We had a few hours to kill before blue hour, so we decided to head down the hill and under the deck of the bridge. I hadn't been to the spot since 2009, so I definitely wanted to check it out again. Getting down there is normally a bit of work, never-mind the teams of CHP that were patrolling the island and the bridge. We shot from this spot for about 1/2 hour before heading back up the sandy, dried out hillside. Shooting during the day definitely has lots of challenges with glare, but the fog rolling in was too captivating to pass up. It was hard to leave the spot knowing that it would probably look epic for the blue hour. But I originally had gone with the intent of catching the new span at twilight, so I would have to settle with this scene. Fine by me! San Francisco, CA

description._content: website | blog | facebook | pinterest | 500px This is a shot of the San Francisco Ferry Building. I have always wanted to get a nice shot of the building but the lights below make it hard to do that, after some exploring around I found this place. This is shot from the Hyatt across the street in their fire escape. As I was shooting this I surprised a worker there, he opened up the door to get some fresh air and he saw me with my tripod setup taking this shot, definitely not what he was expecting on his break.
